Author::::Gambetta
DateTime::::2016-03-08T08:29:21Z
There are no EPR reactors in operation because they are a new design.That too (and the fact that France destroyed the industrial sector and knowledge base which allowed its existing reactors to be built and had to start from scratch) is why the first ones are taking so long to build.When they are running, each plant will produce double the power of AGR reactors.The trouble with trying to build another AGR reactor is that, even more than in France, all the skills and knowledge about how to build them has been destroyed through neglect.Drawing something on paper / computer is one thing. Knowing how to ensure high quality concrete is made to the same standards day after day on remote building sites and poured to form a safe reactor surround is another.At least one AGR reactor had to be closed early because the concrete failed because a worker peed in it. The salt from the pea, reacted to the radiation and the concrete started to flake.Similarly in Finland 18 months of work had to be re-done because the sub-contractor did not read the specifications and poured concrete suitable for France and not for Finnish winters.....So to build nuclear power stations (relatively) cheaply, you have to have government policies which ensure there is always at least one site on the go.A bit like solar, where over €1 billion in factory investment has been scrapped in Europe (that includes the UK) because governments first introduced subsidies then took them away...



